==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Shuck
<hw>Shuck</hw> <pr>(sh⟦ucr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A shock of
grain.</def> <mark>[Prev. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shuck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Shuck
<hw>Shuck</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perhaps akin to G. <ets>shote</ets>
a husk, pod, shell.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A shell, husk, or pod;
especially, the outer covering of such nuts as the hickory nut,
butternut, peanut, and chestnut.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The shell of an oyster or clam.</def> <mark>[U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shuck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Shuck
<hw>Shuck</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Shucked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Shucking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To deprive of the
shucks or husks; <as>as, to <ex>shuck</ex> walnuts, Indian corn,
oysters, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To remove or take off (shucks); hence, to discard;
to lay aside; -- usually with <ptcl>off</ptcl>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧<qex>Shucking</qex>⟦rdquo⟧ his coronet, after he had
imbibed several draughts of fire water.</q> <rj><qau>F. A.
Ober.</qau></rj></p>

<p><q>He had only been in Africa long enough to <qex>shuck off</qex> the
notions he had acquired about the engineering of a west coast
colony.</q> <rj><qau>Pall Mall Mag.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Shucker</ent>⟦br⟧
